{"type":"item.started","item":{"id":"item_15","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"cat > .workflow/iphone-app-factory/spec-cross-critique.md <<'EOF'\n# Spec Cross-Critique (Gemini vs Claude vs Kimi vs DeepSeek)\n\n## Verdict\nThe candidate set is **not implementation-safe yet**. There is partial consensus on direction, but the set still contains contradictions, weak acceptance criteria, and App Store 4.3 exposure that would force an implementation agent to guess.\n\n## 1) Consensus\n- Reuse \"'`SwiftAIBoilerplatePro` as the baseline rather than starting greenfield.\n- Drive product definition from research artifacts (App Store reviews, Reddit pain points, competitor scan).\n- Implement in staged slices (foundation -> core -> interface -> integration).\n- Require automated quality checks before release handoff.\n- Include an anti-clone posture (differentiation is required, not optional).\n\n## 2) Contradictions\n- **Boilerplate reuse vs rebuild risk**:\n  - Some candidates imply heavy custom infrastructure creation (new auth/data/design layers) while others require extending existing boilerplate modules.\n  - This creates direct conflict on build scope and timeline.\n- **MVP scope boundary conflict**:\n  - Some candidates include broad “v1+” features in baseline scope; others constrain to smallest differentiated core loop.\n  - No single binding definition of what is in/out for first shippable version.\n- **Validation standard mismatch**:\n  - Some candidates treat simulator/UI smoke as sufficient; others imply full CI, test evidence, and release-ready hardening.\n  - “Done” means different things across candidates.\n- **Differentiation definition conflict**:\n  - One framing treats differentiation as UX polish; another requires unique workflow/mechanic.\n  - App Store 4.3 risk posture changes materially depending on which interpretation is used.\n\n## 3) Missing Acceptance Criteria (Critical)\nMissing or under-specified criteria that block deterministic implementation:\n- Exact **primary user journey** with start/end state and expected persisted artifacts.\n- Explicit **in-scope feature list** for first release and explicit non-goals.\n- Quantified **performance budgets** (cold launch, key interaction latency, memory ceiling).\n- Quantified **reliability budgets** (crash-free target, offline/failure behavior).\n- Quantified **quality gates** (required test suites, pass thresholds, required evidence files).\n- Explicit **data/privacy contract** (what is collected, stored, transmitted, retained, deleted).\n- Explicit **analytics event schema** and acceptance checks for event emission.\n- Explicit **error-state UX requirements** for network/API/storage failures.\n- Explicit **accessibility acceptance criteria** (Dynamic Type, VoiceOver, contrast, tap targets).\n- Explicit **App Store submission evidence checklist** tied to spec requirements.\n\n## 4) App Store 4.3 Risks\nHigh-risk language/patterns that should be rejected or rewritten:\n- “Build a [category] app like top competitors” without a defensible differentiator definition.\n- Feature sets that mirror common boilerplate templates with only cosmetic changes.\n- No required uniqueness test (e.g., differentiator must be visible in first session).\n- No anti-clone acceptance gate in final review.\n\nRequired hardening additions:\n- Define a **Differentiation Contract** with 3-5 concrete product behaviors unavailable in commodity clones.\n- Add a **4.3 Gate**: fail release if differentiators are absent from onboarding, core flow, and screenshots/metadata narrative.\n\n## 5) Boilerplate Rebuild Risks\nAny candidate requiring these without explicit “why existing module cannot be extended” is overbuilding:\n- Rebuilding DI/composition root.\n- Rebuilding design system primitives.\n- Rebuilding networking/storage abstractions already present in boilerplate.\n- Replacing module boundaries instead of adding app-specific features within them.\n\nRequired constraint:\n- Every new infrastructure component must include: `existing module evaluated`, `gap found`, `extension not viable`, `replacement cost/benefit`.\n\n## 6) Testability Gaps\nCurrent candidate set under-specifies testability in these areas:\n- No requirement-to-test traceability table.\n- No per-feature acceptance tests with deterministic setup and assertions.\n- No explicit fixtures/mocks contract for external dependencies.\n- No negative-path test requirements (timeouts, empty states, partial failures).\n- No release-blocking definition for flaky or skipped tests.\n\nMinimum fix:\n- Add a trace matrix: `Requirement ID -> implementation artifact -> test case(s) -> evidence file`.\n\n## 7) Vague / Non-Verifiable Claims (Reject As Written)\nReject terms unless converted to measurable checks:\n- “intuitive UX”\n- “fast and responsive”\n- “production-ready”\n- “secure by default”\n- “high-quality architecture”\n- “App Store ready”\n\nEach must be rewritten as:\n- measurable threshold,\n- test method,\n- evidence artifact path.\n\n## 8) Strict Merge Rules For Next Spec Revision\nThe merged spec should be rejected unless all are true:\n1. Every functional requirement has at least one acceptance test.\n2. Every non-functional requirement has a numeric threshold and verification method.\n3. Scope for first release is explicitly bounded with non-goals.\n4. Differentiation Contract exists and is validated by a 4.3 gate.\n5. No net-new infrastructure is introduced without explicit boilerplate-gap justification.\n6. “Definition of Done” is singular and evidence-based across all phases.\n\n## 9) Implementation-Ready Delta (What to add now)\n- Add requirement IDs (`FR-*`, `NFR-*`) and a full acceptance criteria table.\n- Add an anti-clone Differentiation Contract section with pass/fail checks.\n- Add an infrastructure policy section: “extend before replace” with mandatory justification template.\n- Add a verification section listing exact commands/artifacts required for phase and release gates.\n- Add a traceability matrix linking requirements, tasks, tests, and evidence outputs.\n\nIf these deltas are not applied, implementation will involve guesswork and inconsistent review outcomes.\nEOF'","aggregated_output":"","exit_code":null,"status":"in_progress"}}
